{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72126852-cee7-4799-b5b1-6a5e3d9a4312","content":"In .NET 10, MAUI adopted Android's **edge-to-edge** display by default. The window no longer resizes when the keyboard appears — instead, your app draws behind it. You need to respond to **window insets** to adjust your layout.\n\nHere are two approaches:\n\n## Option 1: Use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (simplest)\n\nWrap your input in a `ScrollView` — MAUI's built-in auto-scroll (enabled by default) will keep the focused `Entry` visible:\n\n```xml\n<Grid RowDefinitions=\"*, Auto\">\n    <CollectionView Grid.Row=\"0\" ItemsSource=\"{Binding Messages}\" ... />\n    <ScrollView Grid.Row=\"1\">\n        <Entry Placeholder=\"Type a message...\" />\n    </ScrollView>\n</Grid>\n```\n\n## Option 2: Handle keyboard insets manually (recommended for chat)\n\nAdd bottom padding to your layout when the IME appears. In your Android platform code:\n\n```csharp\n// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs\nusing Android.Views;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\nusing Microsoft.Maui.Platform;\n\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(\n            Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!,\n            new KeyboardInsetsListener());\n    }\n}\n\nclass KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n{\n    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n    {\n        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());\n\n        // Use the larger of IME or nav bar bottom inset\n        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);\n        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);\n\n        return insets;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis dynamically adds bottom padding equal to the keyboard height, pushing your input bar up.\n\n## Why `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` stopped working\n\nAndroid deprecated `adjustResize` in API 30+. With .NET 10's edge-to-edge default, the system no longer shrinks your window — apps must use the `WindowInsets` API to react to the keyboard. Option 2 above is the modern replacement.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"053692d0-2db2-4db5-98be-2f0a4ec04e5f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` worked in .NET 9 but doesn't work in .NET 10. This is a known change in .NET MAUI — let me provide guidance based on what I know.\n\nIn .NET MAUI for .NET 9 and earlier, on Android you could use `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` to make the layout resize when the keyboard appears. However, this API was deprecated in Android 30+ (Android 11+), and in .NET 10, MAUI moved to using the newer `WindowInsets` API approach.\n \nIn .NET 10, the framework now handles keyboard management through `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`, which should automatically keep focused inputs visible when the keyboard appears. If that's not working as expected for a chat-style layout, you might need to configure the Android manifest directly with `adjustResize` mode or implement custom inset handling to manage the keyboard behavior properly. The real issue is that .NET 10 switched to edge-to-edge rendering by default on Android, so the old `adjustResize` approach no longer works—instead, I need to handle `WindowInsets` directly by adding bottom padding when the keyboard appears, or rely on `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` to manage this automatically.","outputTokens":1693,"requestId":"A847:211CBF:7182A9:82F9AD:69FBE593"},"id":"a2b93edb-5de7-4399-8daf-6fa76f77a7dd","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:07:02.321Z","parentId":"6f019658-9f88-4365-af8e-6a3dfa5c9426"}
